WHEREAS, Senator Sasser was universally respected by colleagues on both sides of
the aisle for his thoughtful, thorough, and bridge-building approach to legislating that allowed
him to pass significant fiscal reform measures and successfully eliminate the federal deficit for
the first time in a generation; and
WHEREAS, from 1996 to 1999, Senator Sasser served as the United States
Ambassador to China under President Bill Clinton, where he worked to improve relations
between the two countries and arranged mutual state visits; and
WHEREAS, after his service as U.S. Ambassador to China, Senator Sasser served as a
visiting professor at George Washington University and later as a professor at the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill; and
WHEREAS, Senator Sasser was also deeply devoted to his family, and he always
endeavored to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, Senator Sasser enjoyed the loving companionship of his wife of sixty years,
Mary Gorman Sasser, and was the proud father of James Gray Sasser and Elizabeth Sasser
and the doting grandfather of four grandchildren; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his wife, children, and grandchildren, he will be sadly mourned
but fondly remembered by his sisters, Jo Marilyn O'Brien and Phyllis Donnally, and a host of
dear friends and former colleagues; and
WHEREAS, on November 3, 2024, a celebration and thanksgiving for the life of Senator
Sasser was held at Second Presbyterian Church in Nashville, Tennessee, which featured family
remembrances by members of his family, including James Gray Sasser, Elizabeth Sasser,
Martha Gray Sasser, Ella Parrott, and Mary Hayden Sasser, a reading by Atticus Parrott, a
eulogy by historian and author Jon Meacham, and remarks by Vice President Albert Gore, Jr.,
Senator Christopher John Dodd, and Dr. David Kidd; and
